Currently these events are added as global entries, making it

difficult to see all of them together. With this change they will all

appear under the same NETWORK_CHANGE_NOTIFIER source type.



Before:

Source type:NONE, Description: SPECIFIC_NETWORK_MADE_DEFAULT, Entry:

t=97 [st=0] SPECIFIC_NETWORK_MADE_DEFAULT

--> changed_network_handle = 101

--> changed_network_type = "CONNECTION_4G"

--> current_active_networks.101 = "CONNECTION_4G"

--> current_active_networks.104 = "CONNECTION_WIFI"

--> default_active_network_handle = 101

Source type:NONE, Description: NETWORK_IP_ADDRESSES_CHANGED, Entry:

t=97 [st=0] NETWORK_IP_ADDRESSES_CHANGED

Source type:NONE, Description: NETWORK_CONNECTIVITY_CHANGED, Entry:

entry.title: Add more functionality to set local password input element
entry.content:
This element asks the user to enter a local/device password and confirm

it. The element will be used during onboarding/OOBE and on the ChromeOS

settings page.



Previously the element contained only two password inputs and delegated

most functionality to its parent element. With this change, more

functionality resides in the input element:



- Placeholder and error tooltips are now hardcoded in the input

elements, since they're shared between OOBE and settings.

- The element now handles checking the the password complexity and that

the two user-entered values agree.

- The element now handles traversal between the two password inputs

itself, and only fires events when a password input is available

(i.e., when the user-entered password passes validation).



The commit also changes the name of the element from

local-password-input to set-local-password-input, since only the latter

communicates that the element asks for a new password and is not

suitable for asking the user for their existing password.



Screenshot: https://screenshot.googleplex.com/8WATn4b3Ci7LAL7

entry.title: Remove WebURLRequestExtraData.url_loader_throttles_
entry.content:
Currently when blink fetches a request, WillSendRequest() methods [1]

create URLLoaderThrottles, and set them to WebURLRequestExtraData.

And URLLoader::Context::Start() takes them from the

WebURLRequestExtraData.



This CL changes it to create URLLoaderThrottles in

ResourceFetcher::LoaderFactory::CreateURLLoader() method [2]. And pass

them directly to the constructor of URLLoader.



This should not introduce any behavior change. This CL is a preparation

for the off the main thread resource loading project. We want to keep a

URLLoaderThrottleProvide in the background thread instead of passing

URLLoaderThrottles from the main thread to the background thread every

time for each request. It is because passing a URLLoaderThrottle to

another thread may require IPC call in the browser thread

(eg: safe_browsing::MojoSafeBrowsingImpl::Clone()) which is not good for

the performance.



[1] RenderFrameImpl::WillSendRequest() for frames,

DedicatedOrSharedWorkerFetchContextImpl::WillSendRequest() for

dedicated workers and shared workers,

WebServiceWorkerFetchContextImpl::WillSendRequest() for service

workers.

[2] LoaderFactoryForFrame::CreateURLLoader() for frames,

LoaderFactoryForWorker::CreateURLLoader() for workers,

entry.title: [//gpu] Eliminate ScopedRestoreTextureBinding
entry.content:
This CL eliminates ScopedRestoreTextureBinding in favor of its one

client using the common gl::ScopedRestoreTexture utility. To make this

change a functional no-op, we add parameterization to

gl::ScopedRestoreTexture. In a future CL we will unify behavior with a

Finch killswitch - the parameterization is for the behavior when the

binding at construction time doesn't refer to a valid texture ID, and

my strong hunch is that it doesn't actually matter whether we restore

to 0 (gl::ScopedRestoreTexture behavior) or the invalid

construction-time binding (ScopedRestoreTextureBinding) in that case.



Note: The third ScopedRestoreTexture implementation in the codebase

shares the behavior of ScopedRestoreTextureBinding, so I will reuse

the parameterization added here for that conversion (and then similarly

look to eliminate it).

entry.title: CrOS Settings: Use empty owner email when none is populated
entry.content:
ownerEmail is supposed to contain the email of the owner when

the current user is not the owner and the OS channel cannot

be changed. The empty value was already used for cases when

there's no owner yet or the device is managed.



Some WebUI tests emulate that the current user is not the owner

without configuring it on the C++ side. That results in

ownership sometimes being taken (depending on the timing) and

ownerEmail not being populated because the OS channel is

expected to be changeable.



Use the empty value to fix the tests.

If the empty value is ever used during a real usage, the user

will be told that only the owner can modify the value (without

specifying who's the owner), which is a safe fallback.

entry.title: Locate parent fragment of nested OOF multicol correctlier.
entry.content:
Fix a mistake from crrev.com/c/4798090 . We shouldn't require the

multicol container that we stop at to be in-flow.



The only actual code change here is precisely that: We will still stop

searching when an entry in the containing block chain is in-flow and the

containing block of that one is a fragmentation context root (e.g.

multicol container), but don't require this fragmentation context root

to be in-flow. It's the right container of the inner OOF multicol

regardless of that.



The rest of the code changes are just an attempt to make it a bit more

readable. We were skipping one element in the chain (the containing

block of the OOF input multicol container box), and went directly to the

containing block of that one. It really shouldn't matter in practice,

because if the containing block (CB) of the OOF input multicol container

box also is a multicol container, we're not going to stop there anyway,

because the fragments of the OOF input box still must belong higher up

in the tree, participating in an outer fragmentation context, because we

can be sure that CB isn't the outermost fragmentation context, because

in that case we would still be inside its layout algorithm, and

therefore wouldn't have to mutate its fragment (since it wouldn't exist

yet), so we won't be here in such cases. But, unlike this paragraph of

explanation, the code is a bit easier to follow, if we start at the

input box itself.

entry.title: [Office] Fix disabling multiple ODFS volumes
entry.content:
Disabling a volume on the UI involves removing the associated item from

the directory tree so that it can be redrawn. To do so, we were using a

`for of` loop to find and remove the disabled volume from the tree.



The array iterator used in a `for of` loop increments an array index

to select the next element to iterate on. When an element is removed

from the array during the iteration, the next element (which we may

want to remove too) can therefore be skipped.



Replace the `for of` loop with a regular `for` loop so that the

current iteration index can be controlled.



Bug: b:293547300

entry.title: login: Call completion callback on LoginDisplayHost destruction
entry.content:
This CL lets LoginDisplayHost calls completion_callbacks_ added from

Finalize or StartUserAdding immediately on destruction for all derived

classes by followings:

* {Fake, Mock}LoginDisplayHost calls completion_callbacks_.



We should call completion_callback_ immediately instead of posting to

SingleThreadTaskRunner for LoginDisplayHostCommon, but we need to fix

UserAddingScreen ownership beforehand which will be done in the next cl.



For now, UserAddingScreen is never destroyed, so calling

completion_callbacks_ asynchrounsly does not cause a memory leak.



This CL also changes user_adding_screen.cc to resolve IWYU.
